  {
    "id": "UgxRZArxjYkdG81lrT94AaABAg",
    "author": "@some-other-guy",
    "author_channel_id": "UC1bv5ydCETOKosx59xFzshQ",
    "text": "i tried this before, but just couldn't cut the disc to to a precise enough circumference to perfectly align the gap between the belt's first and last tooth. PI times the slightest diameter offset always turned out to be far off, so i gave up",
    "likes": 1,
    "published_at": "2024-09-20T22:30:40Z",
    "reply_count": 1,
    "replies": [
      {
        "id": "UgxRZArxjYkdG81lrT94AaABAg.A8cTzVm5D0EA8cbLVPF8l4",
        "author": "@ThinkingandTinkering",
        "author_channel_id": "UC4AkVj-qnJxNtKuz3rkq16A",
        "text": "pick a larger tooth gap and don't be too anal about exactly right mate - i have made quite a few of these and had one failure when i took a bit too much off the disk - but the rest worked just fine - they are never going to be super accurate - if you want that kind of engineering you will have to invest in the tools to get it - but they are accurate enough and that is all you can realistically expect tbh",
        "likes": 1,
        "published_at": "2024-09-20T23:43:42Z"
      }
    ]
